defaultCI
defaultHT welcomes the recognition of 
defaultthe importance of 
defaultcertainty of investment an
defaultd reform to the Highways Agency set out in Action for Roads. 
defaultMore radical changes to the management of the network may have the capacity for greater improvements in the longer ter
defaultm 
defaultand it is encouraging
default that such options have been considered in Action for Roads.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe standard of highway expertise in the 
defaultUnited Kingdom
default is very high and is recognised worldwide. Our networks are amongst the safest in the world and our professional stan
defaultdards are highly regarded. The 
defaultUnited Kingdom
default has contributed significantly to the development of highways as an increasingly more efficient sector of industry.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is therefore appropriate that Action for Roads proposes an incremental change to the 
defaultmanagement of the Strategic road network that builds on that expertise. Nevertheless the changes that are required do require 
defaulta boldness
default in approach so that the investment proposed can be used effectively to deliver real improvements to customers over time
default.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultCertainty
default,
default and continuity
default of investment over a sustained period is important if overall improvements to the network are to be delivered effectively and efficiently. This need for certainty applies both to the reformed Highways Ag
defaultency and other “client” bodies and the wider supply chain of organisations working in the sector.
default&#xa0;
defaultGovernment needs to provide the certainty required by the supply chain side of the sector to invest in resource and capability to deliver the investment envi
defaultsaged. 
defaultThe Roads Investment Strategy needs to be confirmed and be committed to quickly by all parties. 
defaultThis will allow the Highways Agency to develop a robust pipeline of requirements for its supply chain in a form that allows the supply chain to 
defaultinnovate and invest over a period of time.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultCIHT 
defaultargues
default that there is a clear need for a tra
defaultnsportation strategy that sets a 
defaultclear framework of requirements over a sustained period fo
defaultr all elements of our transportation 
defaultnetworks. 
default 
defaultThis strategy (or strategies) should include the strategic and local road networks,
default r
defaultail, aviation and ports and set
default out how those networks integrate with one another.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe publication of Action for Roads is welcome in that it 
defaultsets out the importance of t
defaulthe strategic road network and 
defaultaims to define the needs of the strategic road network, linking investment over a period to the management structure required to deliver it. There is a concern that the absence of a national transport strategy (or strategies) 
defaultmay mean that the investment identified in Action for Roads is not utilised effectively. The strategy should cove
defaultr
default other transport modes and importantly the overarching policy for the local roads network.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn developing its approach the government needs t
defaulto ensure that the importance of understanding how customer needs are addressed in the new model for operation and be specific about how those needs are developed, protected and monitored by a regulator or other arrangement.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe government needs to be bold in recognising the capabilities required of a reformed Highways Agency. Those capabilities are likely to include a clearer appreciation of customer requirements and an expanded commercial capability, informed 
defaultby other sectors. There is also a need for the reformed organisation to have more freedom to allow more innovation and more agility in decision making.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultGovernment should recognise that the success of an improved 
defaultstrategic network in meeting customer needs cannot be met without the local road network being also considered as part of a holistic solution that customers require.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Department for Transport and government need to clearly define the role of the transp
defaultortation network in delivering the policies of the government. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAction for Roads envisages the publication of a draft national policy statement on national networks in 2013. This needs to clearly set out the relationship of the strategic network to other 
defaultnetworks, including the local highway network. It also needs to demonstrate how the policy links to both national and local planning policy, setting out a clear framework for the responsibility and accountability of developing the network.
